  <datafield tag="245" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Kinematic formulas for sets defined by differences of convex functions</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="260" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="c">2017-03-10</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">The class <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mtext>WDC</mtext><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> consists of all subsets of a smooth manifold M that may be expressed in local coordinates as sufficiently regular sublevel sets of DC (differences of convex) functions. If M is Riemannian and G is a group of isometries acting transitively on the sphere bundle SM , we define the invariant curvature measures of compact WDC subsets of M , and show that pairs of such subsets are subject to the array of kinematic formulas known to apply to smoother sets. Restricting to the case <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>M</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>G</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></msup><mo>,</mo><mover accent="true"><mrow><mi>S</mi><mi>O</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>d</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>‾</mo></mover><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></math> , this extends and subsumes Federer's theory of sets with positive reach in an essential way. The key technical point is equivalent to a sharpening of a classical theorem of Ewald, Larman, and Rogers characterizing the dimension of the set of directions of line segments lying in the boundary of a given convex body.</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">Elsevier</subfield>
  </datafield>
